<font color="#FF0000">DECISIONS &amp; THE RIVER OF LIFE</font><br>
<tt>Sun Nov  2 21:57:04 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Paul,<br><br>
You've hit on a very tough question to answer, but I will try.  May answer may be somewhat different than others, because my thoughts on the subject cannot coelesce upon any one thing.  <br><br>
All people seek meaning and, to some degree at least, harmony with their surroundings as a means of understanding who we are, and how we fit into the scheme of things.  But for the Vietnam Veteran, this is difficult to achieve.<br><br>
It is said of Chaos Theory that the beating of a butterfly's wings, small as the disturbance seems, can impact weather systems thousands of miles away and years into the future.  <br><br>
But Vietnam was no small event--it was a major dislocation of people, of ideas, of cultures, of political theories, of environmental concerns, of animal populations, of just about everything having to do with existence.  If there had been no Vietnam War, every human being in the world would be somewhat different!  The lives lost are not just lost to this generation, but the future generations which would have occured will not now have a chance to come into being.  <br><br>
As mentioned above, we are all &quot;slightly warped&quot; or more by this event.  The effects will continue for generations to come.  <br><br>
Why am I looking at this in this manner now?  Well, I've found out things I did not know a year ago when I started writing on this site.  I did not know, for instance, the fate of Jolly 365 until just recently, or other losses of friends.  Just knowing changes a person's perspective somewhat.<br><br>
I have mentioned before that I would not be married to the same gal who is my wife now, nor have the same kids, or ever live in the same place, except for this war.  Everything changes when a life-changing decision is made.<br><br>
I would not now change those decisions; but I also now know that if some of our political leaders had made different decisions, or if for instance President Kennedy had lived to serve out his term, and perhaps a second, many many lives would be different now.  <br><br>
Our nation has undergone a number of substantial traumas in the last 40 years.  I cannot begin to fathom the extent that things would be different if just one of those had turned out differently.  The &quot;what if?'s&quot; are staggering to contemplate.  <br><br>
The element that changed the course of my &quot;River of Life&quot; was the decision to enlist in the USAF, and then to volunteer for Pararescue.  Those were the two life-defining events.  They changed the course of my travels from civilian student to military enlisted man, and rescue work.  They gave me a motto for my life, and a reason for existence.  Had just one of those decisions been different, every other aspect of my life would have changed.<br><br>
Now, knowing what we know, and being a minority opinion (usually) Vietnam Veterans have a hard time finding that harmony people long for.  In a sense, we have seen too much, too often, too close up, too real; we know the consequences of actions and decisions.  
<p><code>-- searat@sorcom.com  (John C. Ratliff) </code><p>


